1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:07,840
Classic patterns like triangles, wedges or head 
and shoulders are just bait for retail traders. 

2
00:00:07,840 --> 00:00:12,960
And the market is built to trap those 
who follow the same old chart setups. 

3
00:00:12,960 --> 00:00:17,644
Today it’s time to learn the 
patterns the pros actually chase!
  

4
00:00:17,644 --> 00:00:20,320
Over-and-Under – Quasimodo pattern
The Over-and-Under pattern, also called  

5
00:00:20,320 --> 00:00:26,960
Quasimodo, is one of smart money’s favorite 
setups. It’s about sudden changes and traps. 

6
00:00:26,960 --> 00:00:32,480
It all starts with a strong move up. 
Price makes a high. It pulls back,  

7
00:00:32,480 --> 00:00:37,920
then pushes higher, making a new 
high. After that, price falls sharply,  

8
00:00:37,920 --> 00:00:44,480
breaking below the low of the last dip. 
 
This is the key moment! Price makes a lower low,  

9
00:00:44,480 --> 00:00:51,840
taking out stops placed by traders who went long 
earlier. This dip below the last low is fast,  

10
00:00:51,840 --> 00:00:58,640
almost like someone grabs liquidity and runs.
The move is deep enough to scare holders out. But  

11
00:00:58,640 --> 00:01:05,840
instead of rolling over, price snaps back up right 
away. Sellers who chased the low get trapped. 

12
00:01:05,840 --> 00:01:10,880
Now, the market shifts. Price climbs, 
but this time, it doesn’t reach the old  

13
00:01:10,880 --> 00:01:17,520
high. It stalls and starts to turn down 
earlier. This creates a “lower high.” 
  

14
00:01:17,520 --> 00:01:24,000
The Over-and-Under pattern gets its name from 
this exact sequence: a fake-out higher high,  

15
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:30,640
a fake-out lower low, followed by a lower 
high. The pattern is about the trap. Big  

16
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:37,680
money creates the lower low to pull in sellers 
and force out buyers, then reverses back up so  

17
00:01:37,680 --> 00:01:44,560
quickly that most can’t react. The new lower 
high is the spot where the trap closes.
  

18
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:50,960
Here’s how to trade it. When you see price drop 
below support and snap back, mark that low as  

19
00:01:50,960 --> 00:01:57,840
the “liquidity grab.” Watch as price rises 
again. If it fails to reach the old high and  

20
00:01:57,840 --> 00:02:05,040
starts to fall, this is the “over-and-under.”
The lower high is your entry zone. Sell short  

21
00:02:05,040 --> 00:02:10,400
as price turns down from this area. 
Your stop goes just above the lower  

22
00:02:10,400 --> 00:02:18,160
high. If price returns above that, the pattern 
failed. If not, you’re in for the ride down.
  

23
00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:25,200
This pattern works because many traders put their 
stops under the old low. When price drops and  

24
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:32,640
breaks that level, those stops trigger, giving big 
players the liquidity they need to enter or exit  

25
00:02:32,640 --> 00:02:40,080
quietly. After the trap, the market structure 
changes. It’s no longer making higher highs.  

26
00:02:40,080 --> 00:02:47,360
Instead, it prints a lower low and then a lower 
high. This switch signals that the uptrend is  

27
00:02:47,360 --> 00:02:54,000
likely over, and a downtrend may be starting.
 
The best Over-and-Under patterns happen after  

28
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:00,880
a clear uptrend, when lots of traders are 
caught off guard. Volume often spikes during  

29
00:03:00,880 --> 00:03:07,920
the liquidity grab, showing that big players 
are active. The lower high forms quickly,  

30
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:13,600
often with less energy than the earlier 
moves up. The rejection is sharp.
  

31
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:20,960
So to spot this in real time, watch for three 
things. First, a strong move up with a clear high  

32
00:03:20,960 --> 00:03:29,600
and a clear low. Second, a sudden break below the 
low, followed by a quick reversal back up. Third,  

33
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:35,600
a lower high forming as price fails to 
reach the old high. When you see this,  

34
00:03:35,600 --> 00:03:42,240
get ready. The lower high is your short entry. 
Set your stop above it, and look for price to  

35
00:03:42,240 --> 00:03:46,712
make new lows as the trend shifts down.
 
Wyckoff “Spring” (after Accumulation) 

36
00:03:46,712 --> 00:03:52,400
Wyckoff Spring is one of the most common fake 
breakout patterns, to shake out weak traders. 

37
00:03:52,400 --> 00:03:58,320
Picture a price chart with sideways movement.
The price bounces up and down between two  

38
00:03:58,320 --> 00:04:01,200
lines, a top and a bottom.
Traders call this a range.  

39
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:07,760
They buy at the bottom, sell at the top. But the 
market has a trick up its sleeve. This is where  

40
00:04:07,760 --> 00:04:12,640
the Wyckoff “Spring” pattern comes in.
 
The “Spring” happens after a time of  

41
00:04:12,640 --> 00:04:19,440
sideways trading, near the bottom of that range.
Price slowly drops right through the support line,  

42
00:04:19,440 --> 00:04:26,080
just enough to make everyone think the range is 
broken. Traders panic. Some who bought at the  

43
00:04:26,080 --> 00:04:33,360
bottom sell fast to cut their losses. Others go 
short, betting the market will keep falling. This  

44
00:04:33,360 --> 00:04:39,840
is what big players want. They set the trap.
 
Here’s the key: the drop below support doesn’t  

45
00:04:39,840 --> 00:04:45,920
last. It’s quick, sharp, and then, just as 
suddenly, price snaps straight back inside  

46
00:04:45,920 --> 00:04:51,840
the range. The bounce is hard and fast. 
The market shakes out the “weak hands”,  

47
00:04:51,840 --> 00:04:58,800
traders who panic and sell at the worst time. 
This flush is not random. The large players,  

48
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:05,120
the ones with deep pockets, use this moment to buy 
what the weak hands are selling. They want to buy  

49
00:05:05,120 --> 00:05:12,240
big, but they want to do it quietly. If they just 
buy in the range, the price would rise too soon,  

50
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:18,320
so they use the “Spring” to buy from scared 
sellers without tipping off the crowd.
  

51
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:24,560
You can spot the Spring by watching for a dip 
below the lowest point of the range, followed by a  

52
00:05:24,560 --> 00:05:32,880
fast return inside the range. Volume often spikes. 
It shows big players are active. When price comes  

53
00:05:32,880 --> 00:05:39,600
back inside the range, that’s the signal. Now, 
you want to buy! Place your stop just under the  

54
00:05:39,600 --> 00:05:46,400
lowest tick of the Spring. If price returns 
below that point, the pattern failed. If not,  

55
00:05:46,400 --> 00:05:53,040
you ride the next move up, when the market finally 
breaks out for real and price runs higher.
  

56
00:05:53,040 --> 00:05:59,760
On the flip side, after an uptrend and a period 
of distribution (where big players sell to late  

57
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:05,920
buyers), you get the opposite pattern: the 
Up-Thrust After Distribution. The price sneaks  

58
00:06:05,920 --> 00:06:13,360
above the top of the range, often in a sharp move. 
Traders think this is a breakout. They pile in,  

59
00:06:13,360 --> 00:06:20,400
buying the “new high.” But then, price slams back 
below the range top. That breakout was a fake.  

60
00:06:20,400 --> 00:06:25,840
The big players used it to dump their 
inventory on eager buyers. The market  

61
00:06:25,840 --> 00:06:32,720
can’t hold the higher price. The reversal is fast 
and deep. This is the last bull trap before the  

62
00:06:32,720 --> 00:06:39,360
markdown phase, where price drops hard.
 
Both the Spring and Up-Thrust show how big  

63
00:06:39,360 --> 00:06:47,120
players use traps. They create fake breakouts to 
shake out weak traders and fill their own orders.  

64
00:06:47,120 --> 00:06:52,960
These patterns show up every day, on all 
markets and time frames, and they offer  

65
00:06:52,960 --> 00:06:59,734
strong entries. That’s how you know the big 
players are moving and the pattern is real.
  

66
00:06:59,734 --> 00:07:02,800
Volume-Climax + Tight Coil
Volume-Climax followed by a tight Coil  

67
00:07:02,800 --> 00:07:09,120
is a pattern that tells you when the big players 
just made their move, finished their business,  

68
00:07:09,120 --> 00:07:15,680
and are getting ready for the next big swing. 
 
Here’s how it works. First, you’ll spot a giant  

69
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:21,120
candle. It’s much bigger than all the 
candles before it. The price shoots up  

70
00:07:21,120 --> 00:07:27,040
or down, covering more ground in a few 
minutes or hours than it did all day. 

71
00:07:27,040 --> 00:07:33,440
The volume on this candle is huge, maybe the 
highest you’ve seen in days or even weeks. This  

72
00:07:33,440 --> 00:07:39,600
isn’t normal trading. This is when big money is 
at work. They’re either dumping a huge position  

73
00:07:39,600 --> 00:07:46,720
(unloading) or snapping up shares (loading up).
This giant candle is the climax. It’s the end  

74
00:07:46,720 --> 00:07:52,960
of one story and the start of another.
 
Right after this, everything goes quiet.  

75
00:07:52,960 --> 00:07:58,880
Price stops moving fast. Instead, you get 
a group of tiny candles. They barely move  

76
00:07:58,880 --> 00:08:06,400
up or down. They sit in a small box, trapped 
between two tight lines. This is the coil.  

77
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:13,440
It’s like the market is holding its breath. 
Volatility drops. Traders get bored or nervous.  

78
00:08:13,440 --> 00:08:19,440
This is where the big players finished their 
work. They bought or sold what they needed,  

79
00:08:19,440 --> 00:08:25,280
and now they’re waiting for the next move.
 
So why does this pattern matter? Because big  

80
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:31,360
money doesn’t just smash the market for fun. 
They move size when they’re ready for a change.  

81
00:08:31,360 --> 00:08:38,080
That giant volume candle means they needed 
to get in or out, fast. The tight coil that  

82
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:44,960
follows means the rest of the market is stuck, 
waiting, not sure what will happen next. But  

83
00:08:44,960 --> 00:08:52,240
volatility always comes back. The market can’t 
stay quiet forever. Sooner or later, price will  

84
00:08:52,240 --> 00:09:00,160
break out of that coil. When it does, it’s usually 
fast and sharp and the next big move is here.
  

85
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:06,080
The trick is watching which way to trade. The 
direction of the giant volume candle tells you  

86
00:09:06,080 --> 00:09:12,800
which way the big money moved. If the climax 
candle is up, it means they bought in a rush.  

87
00:09:12,800 --> 00:09:20,080
If it’s down, they sold hard. After the coil, you 
want to trade in the same direction as the climax,  

88
00:09:20,080 --> 00:09:25,680
because that’s where the force is most likely 
to come back. The break from the coil is your  

89
00:09:25,680 --> 00:09:32,880
entry. The stop goes just outside the coil, 
if the breakout fails, you’re out quick.
  

90
00:09:32,880 --> 00:09:38,000
Volume is the key to this setup. If 
the big candle happens with low volume,  

91
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:45,040
it’s a fake. Only the real, heavy volume bars 
matter. You want to see the spike, the kind of  

92
00:09:45,040 --> 00:09:51,360
volume that stands out on your chart, way above 
normal. That’s when you know the big players are  

93
00:09:51,360 --> 00:09:58,320
active. The coil should have low volume, too. 
That means all the excitement is gone, and the  

94
00:09:58,320 --> 00:10:04,880
market is quiet, waiting for the next jolt.
 
Some traders call this pattern a volatility  

95
00:10:04,880 --> 00:10:12,160
squeeze. But the combination of a volume climax 
followed by a tight coil is special. It tells you  

96
00:10:12,160 --> 00:10:18,480
the market just had all the noise, and now it’s 
setting up for the next big burst. The breakout  

97
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:26,240
that follows is often fast, with price moving 
quickly and cleanly. You won’t have to wait long.
  

98
00:10:26,240 --> 00:10:32,640
This pattern works on all timeframes. You can 
spot it on a one-minute chart, a daily chart,  

99
00:10:32,640 --> 00:10:40,800
even weekly bars. The story is always the same: 
big spike, then silence, then explosion. The key  

100
00:10:40,800 --> 00:10:47,520
is to wait for the breakout. When price busts out 
of the coil in the direction of the volume spike,  

101
00:10:47,520 --> 00:10:49,360
that’s your trade.
 
 
Gap-and-Go 

102
00:10:49,360 --> 00:10:55,520
Gap-and-Go pattern is loud, fast, and 
full of energy. Most traders freeze.  

103
00:10:55,520 --> 00:11:00,880
Some try to fade the move, thinking the 
gap will fill. But in the Gap-and-Go,  

104
00:11:00,880 --> 00:11:06,640
the market leaves those traders behind.
When the market opens, price isn’t where  

105
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:14,160
it closed last night. It’s far above resistance 
or below support. This isn’t a small gap. It’s  

106
00:11:14,160 --> 00:11:22,160
big enough to wake up momentum traders everywhere. 
They see it and get ready to trade. Shorts panic.  

107
00:11:22,160 --> 00:11:30,560
They rush to cover. Buyers want in before the move 
gets away. The first minutes of trading are wild.
  

108
00:11:30,560 --> 00:11:37,680
This gap matters because it’s not random. It comes 
after a long range or a clear area where price  

109
00:11:37,680 --> 00:11:45,280
kept bouncing. The gap blasts right past that. 
It doesn’t pause. Buyers rush in and push price  

110
00:11:45,280 --> 00:11:52,560
even higher. Sellers who bet against the gap can’t 
get out fast enough. The market never comes back  

111
00:11:52,560 --> 00:12:00,640
to fill the gap. That’s the key. Most gaps fill 
later. But not this one. The move holds strong.
  

112
00:12:00,640 --> 00:12:06,880
This pattern is all about momentum. You see a 
small range in the first one to five minutes  

113
00:12:06,880 --> 00:12:15,520
after the open. Price chops up and down, setting 
its boundaries. Traders watch this range closely. 

114
00:12:15,520 --> 00:12:20,960
As soon as price breaks out, either above 
the high of this mini-range for an up gap,  

115
00:12:20,960 --> 00:12:27,680
or below the low for a down gap, they jump 
in. That’s the entry. The stop goes just under  

116
00:12:27,680 --> 00:12:34,560
the low of the small range if you’re long. If 
you’re short, put the stop just above the high.
  

117
00:12:34,560 --> 00:12:41,520
Volume is huge. This isn’t like other days. It’s 
a sign that big money is moving. The crowd wants  

118
00:12:41,520 --> 00:12:48,080
in. The move feeds on itself. People who 
missed the first entry chase. Shorts who  

119
00:12:48,080 --> 00:12:54,960
didn’t cover at the open now scramble. Each 
new high pulls in more buyers. Each new low  

120
00:12:54,960 --> 00:13:02,400
for a down gap brings in more panic sellers.
 
Most traders think: “The gap will fill. It always  

121
00:13:02,400 --> 00:13:09,280
fills!” They try to fade it. But the Gap-and-Go 
pattern is different. The news is too strong,  

122
00:13:09,280 --> 00:13:17,120
or the surprise is too big. The market moves fast. 
The gap becomes the new base. Price almost never  

123
00:13:17,120 --> 00:13:24,320
comes back to fill it, at least not right away.
 
Sometimes, you see a series of gaps like this  

124
00:13:24,320 --> 00:13:31,280
in a strong trend. These are called runaway or 
measuring gaps. They show up when a trend gets  

125
00:13:31,280 --> 00:13:38,240
even stronger and momentum explodes. Each 
new gap is a sign that buyers (or sellers)  

126
00:13:38,240 --> 00:13:44,480
are even more eager than before. The chart 
looks like a staircase, jumping from one  

127
00:13:44,480 --> 00:13:50,400
level to the next without looking back.
 
To catch the Gap-and-Go, you need to act  

128
00:13:50,400 --> 00:13:57,440
fast. Watch for the big gap at the open. Check 
that it’s above clear resistance or below clear  

129
00:13:57,440 --> 00:14:03,760
support. Watch the first one to five minutes. 
Wait for the range to break. Enter with the  

130
00:14:03,760 --> 00:14:10,880
direction of the gap. Use a tight stop. If the 
move fails and price falls back into the gap,  

131
00:14:10,880 --> 00:14:17,120
get out. But if the move holds, you’re in the 
flow with the strongest traders of the day. 

132
00:14:17,120 --> 00:14:23,163
So momentum, volume and speed. That’s 
what the Gap-and-Go is all about. 
  

133
00:14:23,163 --> 00:14:25,360
Rounded Bottom with Volume Divergence
Rounded Bottom with Volume Divergence  

134
00:14:25,360 --> 00:14:31,440
is one of the best reversal patterns.
In this chart, sellers control the market.  

135
00:14:31,440 --> 00:14:38,240
The chart has a clear downward slope. But then, 
the speed slows. The drops get smaller. The  

136
00:14:38,240 --> 00:14:45,840
bounces start to last longer. Price stops making 
sharp new lows and instead drifts sideways. The  

137
00:14:45,840 --> 00:14:52,800
curve starts to look round, almost like a bowl. 
This is the early sign of a rounded bottom.

138
00:14:52,800 --> 00:14:58,640
At the start of the rounded bottom, volume 
is still strong. People are still selling.  

139
00:14:58,640 --> 00:15:06,000
But as price sinks lower, the volume falls too. 
Each wave down has fewer sellers than before.  

140
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:13,280
Buyers are not rushing in yet. They’re waiting, 
watching. The market feels quiet. This tells you  

141
00:15:13,280 --> 00:15:19,680
supply is drying up. Sellers are tired. Big 
money might be stepping in, but they don’t  

142
00:15:19,680 --> 00:15:26,960
want to show their hand yet. Price keeps moving 
sideways and slowly curling upwards. It’s not a  

143
00:15:26,960 --> 00:15:34,080
sharp reversal. It’s slow, gentle, and calm.
 
Now, here’s the interesting part. The price  

144
00:15:34,080 --> 00:15:40,640
starts to rise, but volume stays low. Most 
people think that rising prices mean buyers  

145
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:49,200
are strong. But here, the rise is soft. It’s not 
about enthusiasm. It’s about no one left to sell.  

146
00:15:49,200 --> 00:15:55,760
The big players are quietly buying. They want 
to keep the price low while they collect shares.  

147
00:15:55,760 --> 00:16:00,880
If they bought fast, the price would 
jump and everyone would notice. But  

148
00:16:00,880 --> 00:16:06,480
they want to buy cheap and unnoticed. 
 
As the bottom of the curve forms, you notice  

149
00:16:06,480 --> 00:16:13,680
something else. Each little dip has less volume 
than before. Each bounce up is a bit stronger,  

150
00:16:13,680 --> 00:16:20,800
but still mostly on low volume. This is volume 
divergence. Price is starting to move up,  

151
00:16:20,800 --> 00:16:25,760
but volume hasn’t picked up yet. That’s 
the clue. It’s not the crowd driving  

152
00:16:25,760 --> 00:16:32,240
the price. It’s smart money buying slow 
and careful, soaking up all the supply.
  

153
00:16:32,240 --> 00:16:39,440
At some point, things change fast. Suddenly 
more big candles appear. Volume increases.  

154
00:16:39,440 --> 00:16:45,680
The price shoots up, breaking above the top of 
the bowl. This is the signal. It’s the moment  

155
00:16:45,680 --> 00:16:52,560
when the big players have finished buying. Now, 
they want the price to move. They push hard and  

156
00:16:52,560 --> 00:16:58,960
everyone else sees the move. This is when the 
new trend begins. The burst in volume confirms  

157
00:16:58,960 --> 00:17:05,760
the shift. It isn’t just a slow drift anymore. 
This is a real move, with force behind it.
  

158
00:17:05,760 --> 00:17:11,760
The rounded bottom with volume divergence is a 
strong sign that the market has changed. Supply  

159
00:17:11,760 --> 00:17:19,600
is gone. Demand is building. Control has shifted 
from sellers to buyers. The new trend is here,  

160
00:17:19,600 --> 00:17:24,240
and it’s not just a bounce. It’s 
a move backed by big money.
  

161
00:17:24,240 --> 00:17:29,360
If you want to trade it, you wait for 
the slow curve at the bottom. Watch for  

162
00:17:29,360 --> 00:17:35,920
price to rise while volume stays weak. When 
the big candle appears and volume bursts,  

163
00:17:35,920 --> 00:17:42,880
that’s your entry. The trend is ready to go. Place 
your stop under the lowest point of the curve. 
  

164
00:17:42,880 --> 00:17:49,520
Most traders miss this pattern because it’s slow. 
It doesn’t look exciting. But that’s the point.  

165
00:17:49,520 --> 00:17:56,400
The slow, rounded shape and the quiet volume tell 
you big players are at work. The sudden burst in  

166
00:17:56,400 --> 00:18:03,440
volume is their signal that the game has changed. 
If you spot the pattern and act on the breakout,  

167
00:18:03,440 --> 00:18:06,080
you’re with the money that matters.
 
Inside-Outside-Inside 

168
00:18:06,080 --> 00:18:13,920
The Inside-Outside-Inside pattern is not common. 
Most traders miss it. But when it shows up,  

169
00:18:13,920 --> 00:18:20,320
it means something big might be coming.
 
First, price prints an inside bar. This  

170
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:26,160
candle sits inside the range of the one 
before. It’s small. It shows the market  

171
00:18:26,160 --> 00:18:33,280
is quiet. Buyers and sellers are holding 
back. Some call this a pause or a squeeze. 
  

172
00:18:33,280 --> 00:18:39,280
Then comes the outside bar. This candle is 
wide. It breaks above the high and drops  

173
00:18:39,280 --> 00:18:45,040
below the low of the last bar. It engulfs both 
sides. The market wakes up. This outside bar  

174
00:18:45,040 --> 00:18:51,760
means there’s a fight. Volume often jumps. 
Both buyers and sellers try to take control.  

175
00:18:51,760 --> 00:18:58,720
The range expands fast. Anyone with tight 
stops gets hit. The outside bar is noisy,  

176
00:18:58,720 --> 00:19:03,760
messy, and full of action. This 
is the wide part of the pattern.
  

177
00:19:03,760 --> 00:19:10,960
Right after, another inside bar forms. This 
candle is tight again, sitting inside the high  

178
00:19:10,960 --> 00:19:17,520
and low of the outside bar that just happened. 
The market settles down. The burst of energy  

179
00:19:17,520 --> 00:19:24,400
is gone, but tension is still there. People are 
waiting. No one wants to make the first move. 
  

180
00:19:24,400 --> 00:19:31,360
This whole sequence means pressure is building up. 
The first inside bar shows the market is waiting.  

181
00:19:31,360 --> 00:19:38,240
The outside bar is the spark. The final inside 
bar shows the waiting isn’t over. Something is  

182
00:19:38,240 --> 00:19:44,720
about to break loose. This is what traders call 
a “pending breakout.” Price is about to move,  

183
00:19:44,720 --> 00:19:48,640
but nobody knows which way.
But when price breaks out,  

184
00:19:48,640 --> 00:19:56,480
you follow. If the upper range is broken, you go 
long. If the lower one triggers, you go short. 
  

185
00:19:56,480 --> 00:20:03,280
This pattern works because it traps traders on 
both sides. The first inside bar makes people  

186
00:20:03,280 --> 00:20:10,160
think nothing will happen. The outside bar shakes 
them up, but it’s over so fast, they don’t trust  

187
00:20:10,160 --> 00:20:18,000
it. The last inside bar makes most give up. Then, 
when price finally breaks, it’s strong. There’s no  

188
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:25,120
resistance left. The move can be fast and clean.
 
You see this most on lower timeframes, but it can  

189
00:20:25,120 --> 00:20:32,240
show up anywhere. It means the same thing: the 
market is ready to move big. Patterns like this  

190
00:20:32,240 --> 00:20:38,640
highlight points in market structure where buying 
and selling pressure is about to tip over. 
  

191
00:20:38,640 --> 00:20:43,680
Most traders ignore the inside-outside-inside 
pattern. But it works! If you learn to spot it,  

192
00:20:43,680 --> 00:20:47,600
you can catch eruptions 
before the crowd even notices. 

193
00:20:47,600 --> 00:20:54,000
The pattern gives you tight levels for entry 
and stops. If the move fails and reverses,  

194
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:59,583
you’re out quick. If it works, you’re 
in when the move is just starting.
 
 
  

195
00:20:59,583 --> 00:21:02,480
Three-Line Strike
The Three-Line Strike pattern makes it easy  

196
00:21:02,480 --> 00:21:08,800
to spot when the market is about to move fast.
First you see price moving in a clear trend,  

197
00:21:08,800 --> 00:21:16,000
but it’s slow. Each candle is small, and they line 
up in the direction of the trend, maybe three tiny  

198
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:23,760
green bars in a slow uptrend, or three red ones in 
a slow downtrend. These candles show the move is  

199
00:21:23,760 --> 00:21:30,400
still going, but it’s not strong. People trading 
with the trend are getting tired. Some might  

200
00:21:30,400 --> 00:21:37,120
even start to think about trading the other way.
 
That’s when the big move happens. Out of nowhere,  

201
00:21:37,120 --> 00:21:43,280
a huge candle appears. This one is fast and 
strong, and it moves in the opposite direction  

202
00:21:43,280 --> 00:21:50,320
to the three before. If you were looking at three 
green candles, now you have a big red candle. If  

203
00:21:50,320 --> 00:21:56,880
you were watching three reds, now a green one 
appears. This candle doesn’t just close over  

204
00:21:56,880 --> 00:22:03,840
one or two of the small bars, it swallows all 
three. The body of this big candle completely  

205
00:22:03,840 --> 00:22:10,080
covers the bodies of the three smaller trend 
bars. This is the Three-Line Strike pattern.
  

206
00:22:10,080 --> 00:22:16,160
The pattern is more than just a reversal. 
It’s a small shock. The market was drifting,  

207
00:22:16,160 --> 00:22:23,120
and then someone stepped in with force. The big 
candle shows a sudden change in control. Buyers  

208
00:22:23,120 --> 00:22:29,200
or sellers who tried to fight the trend are 
now wiped out. The pattern tells you there’s  

209
00:22:29,200 --> 00:22:35,760
energy building up. The trend looked weak, 
then got hit by a big move the other way.
  

210
00:22:35,760 --> 00:22:40,320
Now you simply mark the high 
and low of the engulfing candle.  

211
00:22:40,320 --> 00:22:46,000
These two prices are now your channel.
And you wait and focus on the breakout.  

212
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:52,800
Watch for price to push above the high of the 
big candle, or drop below its low. That’s your  

213
00:22:52,800 --> 00:22:59,760
trigger. If price breaks out above the high, you 
enter a long trade. If it breaks below the low,  

214
00:22:59,760 --> 00:23:05,600
you go short. Don’t guess which way it will 
go. Let the market show you. As soon as the  

215
00:23:05,600 --> 00:23:11,680
breakout happens, you enter with the move.
 
Your stop is simple. Place it just on the  

216
00:23:11,680 --> 00:23:16,880
other side of the channel. If you buy the 
breakout above the high, put your stop just  

217
00:23:16,880 --> 00:23:22,880
under the low of the big candle. If you sell 
the breakout below the low, your stop goes  

218
00:23:22,880 --> 00:23:30,640
just above the high. This keeps your risk tight. 
 
The Three-Line Strike pattern tells a story. Small  

219
00:23:30,640 --> 00:23:37,440
candles mean the trend is running out of steam. 
The big candle means a fight for control. This  

220
00:23:37,440 --> 00:23:44,400
strategy works because the big engulfing candle 
is a signal that something important has changed.  

221
00:23:44,400 --> 00:23:50,960
Big traders just made their move, and now the 
rest of the market reacts. The channel gives you  

222
00:23:50,960 --> 00:23:58,943
clear levels to watch. You don’t need to guess or 
hope, you just wait for price to show its hand.
  

223
00:23:58,943 --> 00:24:00,880
Hidden Divergence
Hidden divergence is a pattern  

224
00:24:00,880 --> 00:24:08,720
that most people miss. This pattern happens when 
price and an indicator, like RSI or MACD don’t  

225
00:24:08,720 --> 00:24:15,520
agree. This is not regular divergence, which 
usually signals a reversal. Hidden divergence  

226
00:24:15,520 --> 00:24:21,440
points to the trend continuing, even when 
price action looks tricky. It’s a pattern pros  

227
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:29,280
use to spot real momentum before everyone else.
 
A Bullish hidden divergence happens in an uptrend.  

228
00:24:29,280 --> 00:24:34,960
Price pulls back and makes a higher low, 
but it doesn’t drop as far as before. But  

229
00:24:34,960 --> 00:24:40,800
the indicator makes a lower low. This 
means that, even though price held up,  

230
00:24:40,800 --> 00:24:47,920
the indicator dipped more. The hidden divergence 
says the uptrend will likely continue. You look  

231
00:24:47,920 --> 00:24:55,600
for this when price is near support in an uptrend. 
If you spot it, you can plan to enter long trades,  

232
00:24:55,600 --> 00:25:01,040
betting the trend will keep going.
 
Bearish hidden divergence shows up in  

233
00:25:01,040 --> 00:25:07,840
a downtrend. Price bounces, making a lower 
high. But the indicator makes a higher high.  

234
00:25:07,840 --> 00:25:14,320
The indicator shows more force, even though 
price couldn’t break past the last high. This  

235
00:25:14,320 --> 00:25:20,640
is a sign the downtrend wants to continue. You 
look for this when price is near resistance in  

236
00:25:20,640 --> 00:25:28,000
a downtrend. If you find it, you can plan to 
enter short trades, following the main trend.
  

237
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:33,600
The steps to spot hidden divergence 
are simple. First, mark the trend:  

238
00:25:33,600 --> 00:25:41,600
look for clear up or down moves. Second, wait 
for price to make a swing high or low. Third,  

239
00:25:41,600 --> 00:25:48,240
compare these points to your indicator and see 
if price and the indicator disagree. So price  

240
00:25:48,240 --> 00:25:54,800
makes a higher low, but the indicator makes 
a lower low; or price makes a lower high,  

241
00:25:54,800 --> 00:26:00,000
and the indicator makes a higher high.
 
Hidden divergence tells you something  

242
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:06,880
about the market that price alone won’t reveal. 
It shows when the crowd tries to fight the trend  

243
00:26:06,880 --> 00:26:13,600
but fails. The indicator exposes this hidden 
strength. You don’t see it on price bars,  

244
00:26:13,600 --> 00:26:19,120
but the oscillator drops important clues. 
The market might look weak, but hidden  

245
00:26:19,120 --> 00:26:25,120
divergence says the trend is still alive.
 
You can trade hidden divergence by entering  

246
00:26:25,120 --> 00:26:32,000
in the direction of the main trend. For bullish 
setups, go long when price starts to rise after  

247
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:38,560
the divergence. For bearish setups, go 
short when price starts to fall. Use  

248
00:26:38,560 --> 00:26:46,000
the last swing high or low for your stop. This 
keeps your risk small, in case the setup fails. 

249
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:53,760
This pattern works on any market. But it’s best 
on clear trends, not in choppy sideways action.

250
00:26:53,760 --> 00:26:57,280
Now, if you’re ready for more 
interesting trading guides,  

251
00:26:57,280 --> 00:27:00,720
go ahead and watch one of these videos next!

